%N A391372 a(n) = 2*a(n-1)^2 + a(n-1) + 1 with a(0) = 0.
%C A391372 This quadratic recurrence was given in Problem A6 of the 86th William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition, which can be found in the first Kedlaya link below.
%C A391372 For n>0, the rightmost digit of a(n) cycles through these six values: 1, 4, 7, 6, 9, 2.
%C A391372 For n>0, the digital root (A010888) of a(n) is 1 if n is odd and 4 if n is even. So, these digital roots follow the sequence A010685.
%C A391372 For k>0, a(2^(k+1))-2*a(2^k) is divisible by 2^(2*k+2) but not by 2^(2*k+3). Two proofs can be found in the second Kedlaya link below.
%H A391372 Kiran S. Kedlaya, <a href="https://kskedlaya.org/putnam-archive/2025.pdf">The 86th William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition (Dec 6, 2025)</a>.
